Investigators suspect rebel tribesmen may have been involved in the weekend bombing of a religious shrine in Pakistan's restive southwest that killed 39 people. 
 Police have largely ruled out sectarian rivalry and say Saturday's attack may be linked to bloody clashes two days earlier between government forces and nationalist clans in the unruly province of Baluchistan. 
 UN Secretary General Kofi Annan expressed outrage after the bomb ripped through a crowd of devotees celebrating the anniversary of the death of a 19th century Sufi Muslim saint in the remote town of Fatahpur.